 1. WHAT IS SPARK?
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
- Distributed in-memory computing engine for large-scale data processing.
- Connects with HDFS, JDBC/ODBC, Azure, S3, GCS, MongoDB etc.
- Solves Hadoop's disk I/O problem (MapReduce writes to disk after every step).
- Unified engine: Batch + Streaming + SQL + ML + Graph.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 2. SPARK ARCHITECTURE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
- Master-Slave architecture.
- Flow: Driver → Cluster Manager → Executors
- Cluster Managers: YARN | Kubernetes | Mesos | Standalone

 DRIVER (Master/Brain)
  - Runs main() | Creates SparkSession/SparkContext.
  - Builds DAG → splits into Stages → sends Tasks to Executors.
  - Collects final results.

 EXECUTOR (Worker)
  - Worker process on each node.
  - Runs Tasks, stores cached data (memory/disk).
  - Sends results back to Driver.
  - Each app gets its OWN executors (isolation).

 PARTITION
  - Data split into chunks across nodes (default 128MB per partition).
  - 1 Task = 1 Partition.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 3. MapReduce vs SPARK vs PANDAS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 MapReduce   → Disk-based | Slow iterative | Batch only
 Spark       → In-memory  | 100x faster   | Unified engine
 Pandas      → Single machine only | GB-scale | No fault tolerance

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 4. RDD vs DATAFRAME vs DATASET
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 RDD       → Low-level | Full control | No Catalyst | Unstructured data
 DataFrame → Mid-level | Catalyst optimized | Schema-based | Fast
 Dataset   → High-level | Type-safe | Scala only | Catalyst + Tungsten

 KEY POINTS:
  - Catalyst Optimizer → only for DataFrame/Dataset (NOT RDD).
  - Tungsten Engine    → memory + CPU optimization for DataFrame/Dataset.
  - DataFrame = Dataset[Row] internally → same performance.
  - PySpark has NO Dataset → Python type system mismatch.
  - In Spark 2.x → DataFrame & Dataset merged into Structured API.
  - df.rdd conversion → loses Catalyst optimization.

 PRODUCTION RULE:
  ✔ DataFrame → production use
  ✔ RDD       → custom low-level logic only
  ✔ Dataset   → Scala projects only

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 5. LAZY EVALUATION
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
- Transformations → NOT executed immediately.
- Spark builds a DAG of operations.
- Executes ONLY when Action is called.
  → Actions: count(), collect(), show(), write(), save()
- Benefit: Catalyst Optimizer tunes full plan BEFORE execution.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 6. TRANSFORMATIONS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 NARROW (no shuffle → FAST)
  - Each partition → one output partition independently.
  - Examples: map(), filter(), select(), union()

 WIDE (shuffle required → SLOW)
  - Data moves ACROSS partitions/nodes via network.
  - Examples: groupBy(), join(), sort(), distinct(), repartition()

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 7. LINEAGE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
- Complete history (DAG) of transformations on RDD/DataFrame.
- Immutable + Lineage = RESILIENT (fault tolerant).
- Lost partition → recomputed from lineage (no replication needed).
- rdd.toDebugString() → view lineage graph (read bottom to top).

 Lineage Example:
  rdd1 = read csv
  rdd2 = filter
  rdd3 = join
  rdd4 = save to disk  ← ACTION triggers all above

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 8. DAG → JOB → STAGE → TASK
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 DAG   → Full logical execution plan.
 JOB   → 1 Action = 1 Job.
 STAGE → Split at Wide Transformation (shuffle boundary).
 TASK  → Smallest unit. 1 Task = 1 Partition.

 Flow:
  Action called
    → 1 JOB created
        → split into STAGES (at shuffle points)
            → each Stage → N TASKS (N = partitions)
                → Tasks sent to Executors

