 20. FILE FORMATS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 NOTE: Avro, ORC, Parquet are CONTAINER-BASED file formats (splittable + schema in metadata).

 ROW-BASED: Read entire row even for 1 column → fast write, slow read.
 COLUMN-BASED: Read only needed columns → fast read, slow write, better compression.

 AVRO
  - Row-based | Fast write | Slower column read.
  - Schema stored in header as JSON | Data in binary.
  - Best schema evolution (add/remove/rename columns).
  - Language-agnostic (C, Python, Java, C++).
  - Self-describing (schema + data together).
  - Best for: Landing zone / ETL (read all columns).

 ORC (Optimized Row Columnar)
  - Column-based | Fast read | Slow write.
  - Designed specifically for Hive.
  - Encoding: Dictionary, Bit Packing, Delta, Run-Length Encoding.
  - Predicate pushdown at storage level (reads less data).
  - 3-level indexes: File → Stripe → Row Group.
  - Structure: Header | Body (Stripes → Row Groups 10k rows) | Tail
  - Default stripe size: 250MB.
  - Schema evolution: supported (protocol buffers) but not as mature as Avro.
  - Best for: Hive-heavy workloads.

 PARQUET
  - Column-based | Fast read | Slow write.
  - General-purpose (not Hive-specific like ORC).
  - Best for deeply nested data structures.
  - Schema evolution: add/delete columns from END only.
  - Self-describing (metadata at end of file).
  - Structure: Header(par1) | Row Groups → Column Chunks → Pages | Tail
  - Best for: Spark + nested data + general use.

 FILE FORMAT TRADE-OFF SUMMARY:
 ┌──────────┬────────┬───────┬────────────────┬──────────────────┐
 │ Format   │ Type   │ Read  │ Schema Evolve  │ Best Use         │
 ├──────────┼────────┼───────┼────────────────┼──────────────────┤
 │ CSV/JSON │ Row    │ Slow  │ No             │ Raw/human readable│
 │ Avro     │ Row    │ Medium│ BEST           │ Landing zone/ETL │
 │ ORC      │ Column │ Fast  │ OK             │ Hive workloads   │
 │ Parquet  │ Column │ Fast  │ Limited        │ Spark/nested data│
 └──────────┴────────┴───────┴────────────────┴──────────────────┘

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 21. COMPRESSION TECHNIQUES
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 Trade-off: More compression = more CPU time but less I/O cost.

 ┌─────────┬───────────────┬──────────┬───────────┬──────────────────────┐
 │ Codec   │ Compress Ratio│ Speed    │ Splittable│ Use Case             │
 ├─────────┼───────────────┼──────────┼───────────┼──────────────────────┤
 │ Snappy  │ 1.2x–2x (low) │ FASTEST  │ No        │ General Spark use    │
 │ LZO     │ 1.5x–2.5x     │ Fast     │ YES       │ Speed + splittable   │
 │ Gzip    │ 2.5x–3.5x     │ Slow     │ No        │ Storage savings      │
 │ Bzip2   │ ~9% > Gzip    │ SLOWEST  │ YES       │ Archival only        │
 └─────────┴───────────────┴──────────┴───────────┴──────────────────────┘

 IMPORTANT: Container formats (Avro, ORC, Parquet) = splittable regardless of codec.
 NOTE: More compression → fewer blocks → fewer tasks → SLOWER processing.

 ┌──────────┬──────────────────────────────┐
 │ Format   │ Recommended Codec            │
 ├──────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
 │ Parquet  │ Snappy (default), Gzip       │
 │ ORC      │ Zlib, Snappy                 │
 │ Avro     │ Snappy, Deflate              │
 └──────────┴──────────────────────────────┘

